QUESTION:
2. Given $A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ 3 & 4 \end{bmatrix}$ and $B = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & -1 \\ 6 & 7 \end{bmatrix}$, compute $AB$ and $BA$ to demonstrate non-commutativity.

GOLD_ANSWER:
1. **$AB$**:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
1(0) + 2(6) & 1(-1) + 2(7) \\
3(0) + 4(6) & 3(-1) + 4(7)
\end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix}
12 & 13 \\
24 & 25
\end{bmatrix}
$$
2. **$BA$**:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
0(1) - 1(3) & 0(2) - 1(4) \\
6(1) + 7(3) & 6(2) + 7(4)
\end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix}
-3 & -4 \\
27 & 40
\end{bmatrix}
$$
Thus, $AB \neq BA$.

CANDIDATE_ANSWER:
Step 1: Compute the product AB: 
AB = A * B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ 3 & 4 \end{bmatrix} * \begin{bmatrix} 0 & -1 \\ 6 & 7 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 12 & 13 \\ 24 & 25 \end{bmatrix}
Step 2: Compute the product BA: 
BA = B * A = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & -1 \\ 6 & 7 \end{bmatrix} * \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ 3 & 4 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -3 & -4 \\ 45 & 58 \end{bmatrix}
Step 3: Show that AB is not equal to BA to demonstrate non-commutativity: 
AB = \begin{bmatrix} 12 & 13 \\ 24 & 25 \end{bmatrix} \neq BA = \begin{bmatrix} -3 & -4 \\ 45 & 58 \end{bmatrix}

